for implementation of the recommendations.  In accordance with the RMP program guidelines, the Program contains the following elements:

7 Hazard Assessment, including a worst case analysis, an alternative release analysis, and a five-year accident history;
7 Management Program, including a document management system;
7 Prevention Program, including process safety information, a process hazard analysis, operating procedures, training programs, maintenance programs, incident investigation programs, documentation of compliance audits, management of change procedures, pre-startup review, contractor requirements, employee participation programs, and hot work permit requirements; and
7 Emergency Response Program, including development of a plan and program.

The facilities are in compliance with the requirements of the CalARP and RMP programs.  They are operated with programs that protect both the workers at the facility and the public from accidental release of RSs.  The facilities have implemented detailed training, maintenance, and inspection programs that serve to prevent releases of an RS.  In the event of a release of either chlorine or isopentane, Ogden Geothermal Operations, Inc. has an Emergency Response Plan that provides for the notification of the public and provides steps to mitigate the impacts of a release.

This RMP and CalARP Program documents all of the required information and provides a summary of Ogden Geothermal Operations, Inc.'s plans and programs to manage risks associated with the handling of chlorine and isopentane at the HGC and SIGC facilities.
